Prosper Loan Dataset Exploration¶

by Baki Musa Oladayo¶

Introduction¶

Prosper Loan dataset contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others. I Focused my exploration on about 10-15 variables out of 81 variables in the dataset for easy and proper exploration of the dataset. So, there were needs for droping some of the variable in the dataset. My exploration was focused on predicting factors that affect loans Borrower APR.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 97,886 Loan records in the cleanned Prosper dataset with 15 features (Term , LoanStatus , BorrowerAPR , ProsperScore, EmploymentStatus, EmploymentStatusDuration, AvailableBankcardCredit, DebtToIncomeRatio,StatedMonthlyIncome, LoanOriginalAmoun, MonthlyLoanPayment and CreditScore ). Most variables are numeric in nature, but the variables EmploymentStatus, LoanStatus are Nominal in nature while Credit Score are ordered factor variables with the following levels.

(worst) > (best)

  • Credit Score: Poor: 300579, Fair: 580669, Good: 670739, Very Good: 740799 and Excellent: 800850

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in predicting factors that affect loans BorrowerAPR.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that ProperScore (risk score) will have the strongest effect on the BorrowerAPR and also EmploymentStatus, LoanOriginalAmount, AvailableBankcardCreditCredit, DebtToIncomeRatioCredit and Term will have effects on the BorrowerAPR , though to a much smaller degree than the main effect of ProsperScore.

ProsperScore Variable Distribution¶

In [29]:
#ploting distribution of prosper score using bar chart

total_listings = PLoan_df_clean.shape[0]

# Ploting the prosperscore on a Horizontal bar chart
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
Prosper_score = PLoan_df_clean.ProsperScore.value_counts().index
sb.countplot(data = PLoan_df_clean, y = 'ProsperScore', color = base_color
              , order = Prosper_score); 
plt.xlabel('Count')
plt.ylabel('Prosper score')
plt.title("Distribution of Prosper score")

# retrieve locations of yticks
locs = plt.yticks()[0]

# number of listings in descending order for each score
score_counts = PLoan_df_clean.ProsperScore.value_counts()

for loc, scores in zip(locs, Prosper_score):
    # number of listings for the given Prosper score
    score_count = score_counts[scores]
    
    # calculate the proportion of the score in % [format: score count (proportion)]
    scores_proportion = '{} ({:0.2f}%)'.format(score_count, 100*score_count/total_listings)
    
    # annotate the proportion of the state to the right of its corresponding bar
    plt.text(x = score_count + 1000, y = loc, s = scores_proportion, va = 'center', color = 'black', fontsize = 10)

From the Bar Chart above majority of the prosper borrowers scored 8 (which is low risk) with 15.16% proportion and 1 (very high risk) was the least in the rating with 0.95% proportion. Scores 6,7,8, 9 and 10 which I recognised as low risk rating take highest proportion (57.89%) of the prosper borrowers. This indicate that prosper borrowers generally have low risk arting.

The histogram shown above illustrate that the distribution of the duration of the borrowers' employment statuses when their listings were created in Prosper is right-skewed. The number of borrowers exponentially decreased with longer duration of employment status. The majority of the borrowers' employment status lasted between 0 to less than 100 months. This range includes the center of the distribution observed at approximately 75 months.

In [31]:
# distribution of employment status duration in log scale

log_data = np.log10( PLoan_df_clean.query('EmploymentStatusDuration > 0').EmploymentStatusDuration)
# bin edges for log scale

# histogram with x-axis in log scale

plt.xticks(locs, labels)

plt.title("EmploymentStatusDuration Log Distribution ")
plt.ylabel('Count');

Applying a log transformation to the duration of employment status reduces the degree of right-skewed distribution. However, because significantly small number of borrowers maintained their employment statuses for more than 300 months or 25 years, the distribution of the log-transformed data appear to be slightly left-skewed than normal.

Conclusions¶

My exploration analysis of prosper loan dataset was stated by gathering of data which was downloaded directly from Udacity website and i furthered by assessing the data visually and programatically in which some quality and tidiness issues were noticed and documented. After assessment i proceed to cleaning of the identified issues before i started my visualization exploration.

In the exploration, I found that there was a strong relationship between the Borrowers APR and prospers score which is the ranking of risk of the listing, with modifying effects it was clearly showed that as ARP is decreasing the prosper score increased. Higher Prosper Score leads to Lower ARP, the lower the APR the lower the risk. Exploring borrowers APR with other numeric variables shows that there was negative relationship between borrowers APR and loan original amount and available bank card credit, this shows that the higher the Borrowers APR the lower the loan original amount and the lower the available bank card credit.

With exploration of borrowers APR against selected categorial variables i saw that borrowers APR decreases as the credit score increased, people with a good credit score gets lower interest rate. People with other employment status have higher Borrowers APR when compared with both employed and retired, People who are employed gets lower intrest rate than retired. Borrowers APR decrease as the loan terms increases, borrowers with 60 month loan Term has chances of having low interest rate. I go further by exploring the effect borrowers APR has on loan status outcome, although relationship with loan status categories isn't that consistent but current status tend to have lower BorrowersAPR when compared to others.

In conclusion, i will say that ProsperScore, EmploymentStatusDuration, AvailableBankcardCredit, LoanOriginalAmount, CreditScore, EmploymentStatus and Long Term have a strong effect on Borrowers APR.
